{"cursor":"50638","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"Orion — Aerospace}} {| class=\"wikitable infobox\" style=\"margin:\n0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; width: 22em;\"\n|-\n|+ Orion -\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: white;\" |\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Description\n|- 'Role:' || Beyond LEO, back-up for commercial cargo and crew to the ISS - 'Crew:' || 2â6 - 'Carrier\n|rocket:' || Space Launch System http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-\n|bin/query/D?c111:3:./temp/~c111MS7qB3:: (planned-deep space),\nDelta IV (test flight),\n\nAres I (cancelled)\n|- 'Launch date:' || December 2013 or later (uncrewed test launch) http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2011/09/sls-mission-\n|improving-crewed-moon-mission-2019/ -\n! colspan=\"2\" | Dimensions\n|- 'Height:' || - 'Diameter:' || 5 m (16.5 ft) - 'Pressurized volume:'\n|||  - 'Habitable volume:' ||  -\n|'Capsule mass:' || 8,913 kg (19,650 lb) - 'Service Module mass:' ||\n|12,337 kg (27,198 lb) - 'Total mass:' || 21,250 kg\n|(46,848 lb) - 'Service Module propellant mass:' || 7,907 kg\n|(17,433 lb) -\n! colspan=\"2\" | Performance\n|- ' Total delta-v:' || 1,595 m/s - ' Endurance:' || 21.1 days }\n'Orion Multi-Purpose Crew Vehicle' ('MPCV') is a planned beyond-low-earth-orbit\nmanned spacecraft that is being built by Lockheed Martin for NASA and Astrium\nfor European Space Agency http://www.esa.int/Our_Activities/Human_Spaceflig-\nht/Research/ESA_workhorse_to_power_NASA_s_Orion_spacecraft for crewed\nmissions to the Moon, asteroids and Mars. It is plannned to be launched by the\nSpace Launch System. Each Orion spacecraft is projected to\ncarry a crew of four or more astronauts. It is also\nplanned as a backup for ISS cargo and/or crew\ndelivery, [http://www.nasa.gov/exploration/systems/mpcv/index.html Orion -\nNASA]\n\nThe MPCV was announced by NASA on 24 May 2011, aided by\ndesigns and tests already completed for a spacecraft of the cancelled\nConstellation program, development for which began in 2005 as the Crew\nExploration Vehicle. It was formerly going to be launched by the tested-but-\ncancelled Ares I launch vehicle.\n\nThe MPCV's debut unmanned multi-hour test flight, known as Exploration Flight\nTest 1 (EFT-1), is scheduled for a launch aboard a Delta IV Heavy rocket in\n2014. http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2011/08/oft-1-\nnasa-orions-2013-debut-via-delta-iv-heavy/ http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2011/10/nasa-managers-serious-\natv-role-as-orion-service-module/ The first manned mission is expected to\ntake place after 2020. In January 2013, ESA and NASA announced That\nthe Orion Service Module will be built by European space company Astrium for\nEuropean Space Agency. [http://www.nasa.gov/exploration/systems/mp-\ncv/orion_feature_011613.html NASA Signs Agreement for a European-Provided Orion\nService Module\n","linknr":937,"url":"Orion_spacecraft","recorded":1362267925,"links":90,"instances":["rocket","spacecraft","iss_module","spacecraft","spacecraft","rocket_family","cm","nasa","astronaut","spacecraft","spacecraft","spacecraft","spaceflight"],"pdf":["http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/510449main_SLS_MPCV_90-day_Report.pdf","http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/510449main_SLS_MPCV_90-day_Report.pdf","http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/510449main_SLS_MPCV_90-day_Report.pdf","http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/510449main_SLS_MPCV_90-day_Report.pdf","http://www.planetary.org/programs/projects/aim_for_mars/study-report.pdf","http://www.planetary.org/programs/projects/aim_for_mars/study-report.pdf","http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/133896main_133896main_ESAS_rollout_press.pdf","http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/133896main_133896main_ESAS_rollout_press.pdf","http://www.ostp.gov/galleries/press_release_files/NASA%20Review.pdf","http://www.ostp.gov/galleries/press_release_files/NASA%20Review.pdf","http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/156298main_orion_handout.pdf","http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/156298main_orion_handout.pdf","http://www.californiaspaceauthority.org/conference2006/pdfs/061201-0900-Petersen.pdf","http://www.californiaspaceauthority.org/conference2006/pdfs/061201-0900-